commentBody:
@Puzzlemucker 

I had the same thought when I saw your typo. 

Vladimir begging, “Good god, man, let me the hell out of this play!”

@Al  @ Puzzzlemucker --

Al, thanks for reminding me of my own misspent youth reading Updike before I was ready for him (then, when I was finally old enough to "get" Updike, not really caring about Rabbit's internal life, let alone his life in various beds with various women). I haven't read most of Bellow, including Herzog, but I do like his prose style, sweeping, rich, full of allusions and worldliness -- I just think his male characters, colorful, neurotic, larger than life, full of appetites and contradictions, inclined to self destruction, are showing their age and the baggage of their particular eras, and because of that feeling they're not at the top of the stack of Books To Read.  Speaking of which, I know I am a little behind on our Shakespeare project, Al, and you've been very good about keeping up with it. 

Puzzlemucker, your knowledge of poetry (among other things) always blows me away -- and I loved your recent posts that followed on the two Frost-related puzzles, just brilliant. I'll leave it at that.

@John

I can also imagine it being a way for the editors to have some fun. When I write scholarly papers, I always try to infuse them with a bit of fun, even if I usually do so surreptitiously. Once I managed to insert a quote from a video game into the actual title of my paper (which was about the legal and practical aspects of something completely game-unrelated), another time I snuck in the names of my favorite comic book characters into a footnote (I referenced an article about the language of Polish comics in the socialist era, as it was relevant to a legal argument I was making, strangely enough), etc. I even almost made a bet with a friend to quote a certain adult performer in an article, but in the end I passed on the opportunity.

Possibly the NYT puzzle editors enjoy the challange of having the same answer appear in puzzle after puzzle?

@N 

Do better at understanding clues.  A coset can be a subgroup, therefore the clue is good.  It's not a definition.

If I have a clue "Apple" and the answer is "Fuji" (a perfectly valid clue set) would people complain that fujis are not always apples - sometimes they're mountains?  Maybe in this comment section.

@Jay 

It is practically a given that the words "Do better" in any comment winds up being unintentionally ironic.

(And sometimes apples aren't Fujis; sometimes they're Granny Smiths.)

@Lauren Atlas 

I wonder about solving styles.  I almost never fill in a long one unless I have at least three or four crosses.

Of course that doesn't guarantee you'll have the crosses you need, but it increases the chances you won't end up with poisoned squares.

@alan 

And it’s not just the app.  They also made it clunkier to switch from the column to the puzzle if you use a browser for access.  So, if someone writes about, say, 28 D, and I want to remind myself which one that was, I have to go through 4 clicks (each way, uphill, in the snow, and, in my day,*loving* it!…) to get there and back.  (I suppose I could open up two tabs.)

Not the worst problem of the day, but when interfaces are changed like this I always wonder, “why?  Do the coders even use the product they create or modify?”

@Warren 

Just open two browser tabs, one with the comments, one with the puzzle. (I use xwordinfo.com for the puzzle.)

Easy peasy.

@Kate 

Somehow I don't mind the "French butchery" in today's puzzle, probably because it's so blatantly -- intentionally -- NOT French.

The one that always had me howling is the name of a certain bakery chain. Boy, do Americans massacre that one! As their offerings became less and less authentic -- as they expanded regionally and then nationally -- I began pronouncing the name as butchered as possible! If they weren't going to be authentic, nor would I.... "Oh bawn pain", with the last sounding as in being hurt. 😬

@Nancy 

